    ],
    "acceptance_criteria": [
      "A player on any tier-1 client goes from logged-in to watching their agent play via a universal play-prompt plus a one-time connect step, verified end-to-end on Claude Code, Desktop, Codex, Gemini, and Cursor.",
      "Idle token burn while waiting is cut substantially: next-turn supports a bounded 25-30s long-poll and the idle poll interval is raised, so there is no model call every few seconds while waiting.",
      "The dashboard shows a per-connection usage figure: exact call and turn counts immediately, with a token estimate once calibration exists.",
      "A player who closes their terminal mid-match auto-defaults to Hoard and can rejoin, verified with no new engine code.",
      "No regression to the connector path (shared next-turn endpoint); Preflight Gate green."
    ],
    "checklist": {
      "goal": "Make interactive Mode A play (a player runs their own AI against our existing /mcp server and watches it) cheap enough to leave running and transparent about token cost, so a trust-wary player can play without installing the background connector. v1 = idle-cost reduction (poll-interval bump + bounded long-poll) + a per-connection usage counter on the dashboard + a universal play-prompt and per-client connect snippets, reusing the existing MCP / agent-API / turn-routing stack.",
      "audience": "New or trust-wary players who will not install the background connector (including the alpha user blocked by corporate DNS and by their own AI refusing the install), on any MCP-capable client: Claude Code, Claude Desktop, Codex, Gemini, Cursor. Plus us internally, who need the cost calibration.",
      "constraints": "Long-poll is hot-path concurrency shared with the connector on a single-instance async app (a prior mid-deploy freeze was a turn-routing concurrency bug): must not pin a DB connection while held, must stay under each client request timeout, must interact correctly with the existing atomic sticky-pin claim, and must fall back to the poll-interval hint on timeout or expiry. The usage counter sits on mark_seen, the universal auth choke point, so watch write-amplification (last_seen_at is already throttled). Counter storage likely needs a migration. Interactive Mode A exposes no real token count to the server, so the dashboard figure is an estimate and the players own /cost reading is ground truth; calibration is a one-time internal lab step. Chris executes the per-client verification matrix."
    },
